  "issue_number": 4118,
  "issue_title": "\ud83d\udcdd [Proposal]: Typed binding errors with source and field information",
  "issue_body": "### Feature Proposal Description\n\n`Bind().All()` iterates through sources (URI, Body, Query, Header, Cookie) and returns the first raw error it encounters. Callers have no way to determine *which* source or *which* field failed, because the error is an opaque `error` value from the underlying decoder.\n\nThis proposal adds a `BindError` type that wraps the original error with structured metadata:\n\n```go\ntype BindError struct {\n    Source string // \"uri\", \"query\", \"body\", \"header\", \"cookie\"\n    Field  string // struct field name or tag key that failed\n    Err    error  // underlying error (preserves errors.Is/As chains)\n}\n\nfunc (e *BindError) Error() string { ... }\nfunc (e *BindError) Unwrap() error { return e.Err }\n```\n\nAll `Bind()` methods (`URI`, `Query`, `Body`, `Header`, `Cookie`, and `All`) would return `*BindError` when a field fails to bind. `All()` would return the first `*BindError` it encounters, as it does today \u2014 but now with source context attached.\n\nCallers use standard `errors.As` to extract the detail when they need it:\n\n```go\nvar be *fiber.BindError\nif errors.As(err, &be) {\n    switch be.Source {\n    case \"uri\":\n        // ...\n    case \"body\":\n        // ...\n    }\n}\n```\n\n### Alignment with Express API\n\nExpress's validation ecosystem (express-validator, built on validator.js) returns structured error arrays with `location` (body, query, params, cookies, headers), `path` (field name), `msg`, and `value`. Developers routinely branch on `location` to produce different responses.\n\nFiber's binding layer is more tightly integrated than Express's \u2014 it owns the parsing, not a middleware. That's an advantage: the framework already knows the source and the target field at the point of failure, it just doesn't surface that information today.\n\n### HTTP RFC Standards Compliance\n\nRFC 9110 \u00a715.5 defines distinct semantics for client error status codes:\n\n- **400 Bad Request**: malformed syntax or invalid framing (bad query params, unparseable body)\n- **404 Not Found**: the target resource is not found (bad URI path segment)\n\nToday, when `Bind().All()` fails, the developer cannot tell whether the problem was a malformed URI parameter or a bad JSON field. The only practical option is to return a blanket 400. With source information on the error, developers can map URI binding failures to 404 and body/query failures to 400, as the RFC intends.\n\n### API Stability\n\nThe change is additive and backward-compatible:\n\n1. `BindError` implements `error` and `Unwrap()`, so existing code using `err.Error()` or `errors.Is(err, ...)` continues to work unchanged.\n2. `errors.As(err, &be)` is opt-in \u2014 callers who don't care about the source simply ignore it.\n3. The `Source` values are fixed to the five binding sources Fiber already defines. The `Field` value comes from struct tag keys already resolved during binding.\n\nNo existing API surface changes or deprecations.\n\n### Feature Examples\n\n```go\nToday \u2014 no way to return the right status code from `All()`:\n\n\nvar req struct {\n    ID   uuid.UUID `uri:\"id\"`\n    Name string    `json:\"name\"`\n}\nif err := c.Bind().All(&req); err != nil {\n    // URI parse failure? Body parse failure? No idea.\n    return c.Status(400).JSON(fiber.Map{\"error\": \"invalid request\"})\n}\n\n\nWith this proposal:\n\n\nvar req struct {\n    ID   uuid.UUID `uri:\"id\"`\n    Name string    `json:\"name\"`\n}\nif err := c.Bind().All(&req); err != nil {\n    var be *fiber.BindError\n    if errors.As(err, &be) && be.Source == \"uri\" {\n        return c.Status(404).JSON(fiber.Map{\"error\": \"not found\"})\n    }\n    return c.Status(400).JSON(fiber.Map{\"error\": \"invalid request\"})\n}\n\n\nThe same `BindError` is available from individual methods too, giving structured field information even when the source is already known:\n\n\nif err := c.Bind().Body(&req); err != nil {\n    var be *fiber.BindError\n    if errors.As(err, &be) {\n        log.Printf(\"field %q failed: %v\", be.Field, be.Err)\n    }\n    return c.Status(400).JSON(fiber.Map{\"error\": \"invalid request body\"})\n}\n```\n\n### Checklist:\n\n- [x] I agree to follow Fiber's [Code of Conduct](https://github.com/gofiber/fiber/blob/main/.github/CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md).\n- [x] I have searched for existing issues that describe my proposal before opening this one.\n- [x] I understand that a proposal that does not meet these guidelines may be closed without explanation.",
